1. Definition and core formula
- Hamming distance d(a,b) for equal-length strings/vectors is the count of positions i where a[i] != b[i].
- For binary words a and b (same bit-width), d(a,b) = popcount(a XOR b).
- For code over alphabet size q, Hamming distance applies position-wise; for insertions/deletions use edit distances (Levenshtein).
- Metric properties: non-negativity, symmetry, identity of indiscernibles, triangle inequality.

2. Hamming distance for binary integers (bitwise method)
- Input: two unsigned integers X and Y of equal conceptual width (32, 64, or arbitrary precision).
- Step 1: Compute V = X XOR Y.
- Step 2: Compute Hamming weight of V (number of 1 bits) = popcount(V). The result is the Hamming distance.
- Time complexity: O(popcount(V)) with Wegner method, or O(1) with word-level parallel popcount algorithms using fixed arithmetic operations.
- For arbitrary-length integers use bigint XOR and bigint-aware popcount loop.

3. Hamming weight (population count) algorithms and constants
- Wegner loop (bit-clear): count = 0; while (v != 0) { v = v & (v - 1); count++; }  Complexity proportional to number of set bits.
- Word-parallel add-reduction (tree) method constants for 64-bit (named masks):
  m1  = 0x5555555555555555  // binary: 0101...
  m2  = 0x3333333333333333  // binary: 00110011..
  m4  = 0x0f0f0f0f0f0f0f0f  // binary: 4 zeros, 4 ones ...
  m8  = 0x00ff00ff00ff00ff  // 8 zeros, 8 ones
  m16 = 0x0000ffff0000ffff  // 16 zeros, 16 ones
  m32 = 0x00000000ffffffff  // 32 zeros, 32 ones
  h01 = 0x0101010101010101  // constant for final multiply-sum trick
- popcount64a (naive tree):
  x = (x & m1) + ((x >> 1) & m1)
  x = (x & m2) + ((x >> 2) & m2)
  x = (x & m4) + ((x >> 4) & m4)
  x = (x & m8) + ((x >> 8) & m8)
  x = (x & m16) + ((x >> 16) & m16)
  x = (x & m32) + ((x >> 32) & m32)
  return x
- popcount64b (fewer ops, no multiply):
  x -= (x >> 1) & m1
  x = (x & m2) + ((x >> 2) & m2)
  x = (x + (x >> 4)) & m4
  x += x >> 8
  x += x >> 16
  x += x >> 32
  return x & 0x7f
- popcount64c (uses multiply):
  x -= (x >> 1) & m1
  x = (x & m2) + ((x >> 2) & m2)
  x = (x + (x >> 4)) & m4
  return (x * h01) >> 56  // returns final count
- Lookup-table approach: precompute table[0..65535] with 16-bit popcounts; popcount32(x) = table[x & 0xFFFF] + table[x >> 16].
- Hardware intrinsics: GCC/Clang __builtin_popcount / __builtin_popcountll; x86 popcnt instruction; C++ std::popcount; Java Integer.bitCount/Long.bitCount; BigInteger.bitCount; Python int.bit_count().

4. String/code-point based Hamming distance (Unicode-aware) in JavaScript
- Requirement: treat strings as sequences of Unicode code points, not UTF-16 code units.
- Use JavaScript iterables or Array.from/string[Symbol.iterator] to iterate by code points. Example iteration approaches: for...of, [...str], Array.from(str).
- Use codePointAt(index) semantics when you operate on a string index: codePointAt returns the full code point when index is at a leading surrogate; when index points at a trailing surrogate it returns the trailing surrogate code unit only.
- Algorithm for code-point-aware Hamming distance:
  1. Convert both strings to arrays of code points: ra = Array.from(a); rb = Array.from(b).
  2. If ra.length != rb.length, throw RangeError (strings must match in code-point length for Hamming distance).
  3. Iterate i from 0 to n-1 and count ra[i] !== rb[i]. Return count.
- Time complexity: O(n) where n = number of code points.
- Edge case: grapheme clusters (combined emoji, ZWJ sequences) will be split into multiple code points; decide whether to compare grapheme clusters or code points depending on application.

5. Efficient implementation patterns and complexity
- Strings: O(n) in code points; pre-check lengths and short-circuit on mismatch.
- Integers: convert to BigInt where needed; Wegner loop cost = O(k) where k is number of differing bits; tree/multiply methods have O(1) fixed operations per word.
- Use hardware popcount when available via compiler intrinsics or language standard functions for performance-critical loops.
- For sparse differences (few differing bits) Wegner loop is often fastest.
- For wide fixed-width words and heavy throughput, use vectorized or word-parallel popcount algorithms (popcount64b/popcount64c) or platform popcnt.

6. API/SDK method signatures (JavaScript)
- Function: hammingDistance(a: string, b: string) -> number
  Parameters:
    a: string — must be a JavaScript string
    b: string — must be a JavaScript string
  Behavior:
    If either argument is not a string, throw TypeError('Both arguments must be strings').
    Convert to code-point arrays via Array.from or [...string]. If lengths differ, throw RangeError('Strings must have the same length in code points').
    Return integer count of positions where code points differ.
  Return: non-negative integer.

- Function: hammingDistanceBits(x: number|bigint, y: number|bigint) -> number
  Parameters:
    x: number or bigint — integer value; if number, must be an integer >= 0.
    y: number or bigint — integer value; if number, must be an integer >= 0.
  Behavior:
    Validate types and integer-ness for number inputs. Convert both to BigInt for bitwise XOR: bx = BigInt(x), by = BigInt(y).
    If bx < 0n or by < 0n, throw RangeError('Integers must be non-negative').
    Compute v = bx ^ by.
    Count bits using Wegner loop with BigInt: while (v) { count += Number(v & 1n); v >>= 1n; } or use v &= v - 1n loop incrementing count.
    Return count as Number (safe if count fits in Number range for expected bit-widths).
  Return: non-negative integer representing differing bit count.

7. Configuration options, edge cases, and best practices
- Unicode vs grapheme clusters: choose code-point comparison for general use; for user-visible equality use grapheme-cluster segmentation (Intl.Segmenter or third-party libs).
- String length checks: always compare code-point lengths (Array.from) not .length (UTF-16 code units) when comparing user content or emojis.
- Use BigInt for arbitrary precision integer Hamming distance; avoid Number for large bitfields >53 bits.
- Validation: reject negative integers and non-integers explicitly with TypeError/RangeError.
- Performance: for repeated popcounts on 32/64-bit words prefer builtins (e.g., __builtin_popcount) or language equivalents instead of per-bit loops.

8. Troubleshooting and step-by-step diagnostics
- Symptom: mismatched-length error for strings when identical visual characters reported different lengths.
  Step 1: Inspect using Array.from(str) and [...str] to see code point sequences.
  Step 2: If grapheme clusters are desired, use Intl.Segmenter or a grapheme library to segment and compare.
- Symptom: unexpected high Hamming distance for integers.
  Step 1: Log X, Y and compute X ^ Y; check bit-width assumptions.
  Step 2: If using Number, verify integer-ness and non-negativity. For >53-bit values, switch to BigInt.
- Symptom: performance regression on large arrays of integers.
  Step 1: Profile to see whether popcount is the hotspot.
  Step 2: Replace per-bit loops with __builtin_popcount or std::popcount or vectorized/popcnt instruction.

9. Supplementary technical specifications
- Complexity:
  Strings: O(n) time, O(n) temporary for code-point array if created; can stream iterate O(1) extra memory using two iterators.
  Integers: Wegner O(k) where k=popcount(V); word-parallel O(1) arithmetic ops per word.
- Exact masks and constants (64-bit): m1=0x5555555555555555, m2=0x3333333333333333, m4=0x0f0f0f0f0f0f0f0f, m8=0x00ff00ff00ff00ff, m16=0x0000ffff0000ffff, m32=0x00000000ffffffff, h01=0x0101010101010101.
- Popcount return types: languages typically return an integer type sized to the word-width; JS returns Number; BigInt loops must convert final count to Number if needed.

